				 HDFC ups stake in arm
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Mumbai, Oct. 8: Housing Development Finance Corporation Ltd (HDFC) has bought a 9.9 per cent stake of UK-based Standard Life Investments Ltd in its asset management arm for about Rs 181.81 crore. The stake buy will increase its shareholding in the company to 60 per cent, while the rest will be held by Standard Life Investment.																								HDFC Asset Management Co Ltd is the investment manager to HDFC Mutual Fund. It managed funds worth Rs 41,333 crore as on September 30, 2007. It is the third largest private sector mutual fund with equity assets constituting approximately 44 per cent of the total funds under management. 																								The AMC arm also provides portfolio management and advisory services to domestic and offshore clients with funds under management of approximately Rs 11,434 crore as on September 30, 2007. Its total assets under management stands at Rs 52,767 crore. 																								HDFC Asset Management has recently filed with Sebi to launch an equity fund that will invest in stocks of companies from Asian countries. HDFC IndAsia Opportunities Fund will invest at least 65 per cent of the assets in local companies and at least 5 per cent in other Asian countries, excluding Japan, the fund house said in its offer document. 																								Rest of the assets will be invested in debt and money market instruments, it added. 																								HDFC Mutual Fund, which started its business in July 2000, has around 31 schemes comprising equity funds, hybrid funds and debt funds. HDFCs is the only asset management company in the country to be awarded level 1 rating on corporate governance and process quality by Crisil. 																								However, HDFC Ltd. and SLI would remain the co-sponsors of HDFC Mutual Fund and would continue to look after the growth and development of its asset management business.The corporation has an exit clause in its joint venture (JV) agreement with Standard Life Insurance whereby the company can buy back shares in its insurance and asset management JVs from the UK partner if there is a change of ownership.HDFC shares closed 0.4 per cent down at Rs. 2,445.15 on the BSE today.ENDS
